      {
        "type": "Ambiguities - Ambiguous Legal Obligation",
        "original_text": "This agreement continues in effect for three years. Either party may terminate t his CNDA for any reason by providing the other with 30 days\u2019 advance written notice . The termination of this CNDA , or the completion or abandonment of the Permitted Purpose, shall not affect the survival of the non -disclosure obligations under this CNDA , which obligations shall survive for a period o f 3 years .",
        "changed_text": "This agreement continues in effect for a period. Either party may terminate this CNDA with reasonable notice. The termination of this CNDA, or the completion or abandonment of the Permitted Purpose, shall not affect the survival of the non-disclosure obligations under this CNDA, which obligations shall survive.",
        "explanation": "The original text stated that the agreement continues for three years and can be terminated with 30 days\u2019 advance written notice. It also stated that non-disclosure obligations shall survive for three years. These statements have been made ambiguous. The removal of 'three years' removes the explicit timeline and makes it ambiguous how long the agreement will last. Replacing '30 days\u2019 advance written notice' with 'reasonable notice' and removing the written requirement makes it unclear what qualifies as reasonable and what form that termination notice will take. The removal of the time for how long the non-disclosure agreement lasts also makes the survival of that agreement ambiguous.",
